%Correlation of Linear Decay with CDS Exon Density
\subsection{Linear decay of AS bias is associated with coding sequence density}
Although 5\rq -UTRs were associated with RT density, CDS exons must still be examined as to their contribution to the effect of reduced RTs near the TSS. Since previous studies have shown that AS RT density was reduced within close proximity to exons, the density of CDS within each decile was calculated. Indeed, CDS density increased at a linear rate across gene deciles (figure \ref{fig:cds_noUTR}). The first decile of genes contained more CDS than the second decile.  AS Alu were inversely correlated with this distribution of CDS (R$^{2}$ = -0.94; one-tailed p <  2.64e-05). S Alu, however, were not correlated with CDS (R$^{2}$ = -0.30; one-tailed p = 0.200) 
    
    %Figure CDS (no secondary 5'-UTR)
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{cds_noUTR.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Distribution of Coding Sequence Exons in RefSeq Genes\\}The number of coding sequence exons (CDS) in the sense orientation were normalized by all sense oriented CDS in RefSeq genes.}}
        \label{fig:cds_noUTR}
    \end{figure}
    
    
