%AS bias and tissue-specificity
\subsection{Tissue-Specificity of the Gene Effects AS bias}
Depending on the functional groups of a gene, it has a different chance of containing large amounts of RTs. For example, housekeeping genes have a predictably higher level of Alu frequency than other gene categories. We therefore tested whether AS bias remained linear when subdivided by gene category. The effect of tissue-specificity was tested by both analyzing the slope of the density of AS as well as correlating the distribution of Alu with the distribution of CDS within tissue-specific gene sets. The linear AS slope remained present in housekeeping genes, but it was not maintained in tissue-specific gene sets. Furthermore, the correlation between ASO-RT frequency and CDS distribution was reduced within tissue-specific gene sets (table \ref{table:tiscor}). Although the sample size of each gene set trended with the R$^{2}$, sample size was not significantly correlated with R$^{2}$ (p = 0.062).

